						               													<description>This dice game is designed for the Blinks system allowing competitors to take dice and bet on results.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;SCORING:&amp;#10;Each Blink is worth the amount of points shown on its face (1-6). If you have more than one Blink with the same face value, the duplicates are instead worth 10 each. For example, a player with a 4, a 5, and a 6 has scored 15 points (4 + 5 + 6), while a player with 3 4s has scored 24 points (4 + 10 + 10).&amp;#10;&amp;#10;WIN CONDITION:&amp;#10;The player with the highest point total is the winner.&amp;#10;While this game can be played with more than 2 players, it's recommended that you play with at least 5 Blinks per player for a competitive game. Also, experiment with starting arrangements for more interesting games. Finally, for more advanced play, limit each player to using the re-roll action only once per game.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;SETUP:&amp;#10;12+ Blinks&amp;#10;5-10 Min.&amp;#10;Takeaway Dice is played using Widgets. Place your Blinks together in a cluster and set them all to the Dice Widget. Determine player order, then single- click a Blink to roll all the dice.&amp;#10;                                                                                                     Rolling the dice&amp;#10;GAMEPLAY:&amp;#10;On their turn, each player takes the following actions. First, they may (but don't have to) re-roll all the dice in the cluster. Then they must remove a Blink from the cluster and claim it for their own.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;Not all Blinks can be legally removed from the cluster at the start of a turn. Blinks with neighbors on opposing faces are &amp;ldquo;locked,&amp;rdquo; as are Blinks that, if removed, would fracture the cluster into more than 2 pieces.&amp;#10;Examples of locked Blinks&amp;#10;Players take turns in succession until the last Blink has been claimed. At this point, players add up their score.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;This Game is played with Blinks Widget.&amp;#10;&amp;#10;&amp;mdash;description from the publisher&amp;#10;&amp;#10;</description>
